Introduction: Aim and Experimental Design

Aim: The aim of this study is to investigate the role of IL-17A in the pathogenesis of systemic sclerosis (SSc), a connective tissue disorder characterized by fibrosis and inflammation. The data will help directing and interpreting therapeutic approaches in SSc, since both, IL-17A and TGF-β, are target candidates in clinical trials.

Experimental Design: To evaluate the potential role of IL-17A in the context of fibrosis and to overcome the limitations associated with two-dimensional cultures, a model of fibrosis was enstablished based on repeated injections of TGF-β into normal full human skin cultured in semi-solid agar. Under these culture conditions for up to 9 days, the skin maintained normal morphology with very few apoptotic cells. To extensively evaluate the gene expression profile in this organotypic model after treatment with TGF-β, we performed RNA sequencing. A similar process has been applied with injections of IL-17A and of combined IL-17A and TGF-β.

For the RNA-seq procedure, RNA was isolated from three independent skin donors with mirVana miRNA Isolation Kit from Invitrogen Integrity and quantity of RNA were assessed with Bioanalyzer cDNA libraries were constructed using Illumina TruSeq RNA stranded Kit. Pools of 18 libraries were loaded at 2 nM for clustering on two lanes of a Single-read Illumina Flow cell. Reads of 50 bases were generated using the TruSeq SBS chemistry on an Illumina HiSeq 4000 sequencer. FastQ reads were mapped to the ENSEMBL reference genome (GRCh38.89) using STAR, version 2.4.0j.

Statistical analysis: In the article, library size normalizations and differential gene expression calculations were performed using the package edgeR (Robinson et al., 2010) designed for the R software (Team, 2011). Only genes having a significant fold-change (Benjamini-Hochberg corrected P-value <0.001) were considered for the rest of the RNA sequencing analysis.

Before plotting, we need to apply data transformation. Here we plot the results of the two methods offered by DeSeq2: vst and rlog. In this plot we see the effect of the transformation in action: in the first plot we can notice that lower count genes appear to be scattered. After the transformation (vst or rlog) the counts appear to be “squished” around the mean.

Multiple testing:

We ask: how many genes are differentially expressed based on p-value? We used 0.001 threshold, based on the paper indications.

sum(res$pvalue < 0.001, na.rm=TRUE)

## [1] 17589
sum(res$padj < 0.001, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 581

We subset the results table to these genes and then sort it by the log2 fold change estimate to get the significant genes with the strongest down-regulation and strongest up-regulation. We are also interested in genes with lowest padj and in the count of up regulated and downregulated genes. We use padj instead of p-value. In this way we avoid including too many false positives in our DE genes (benjamini-Hochberg FDR).

Our top 5 genes based on lowest padj are :

ENSG00000244094 -> SPRR2F small proline rich protein 2F [ Homo sapiens (human) ]
l2fc: 6.51788 - padj: 5.40634e-38

This protein is predicted to be involved in keratinization, also termed as cornification. This is a process of cytodifferentiation that the keratinocytes undergo when proceeding from their post germinative state (stratum basale) to finally differentiated. This process may be enhanched during inflammation to allow the replacement of damaged skin cells. (Shetty and Gokul 2012)

The protein can be related to autoinflammatory keratinization diseases. Inflammation caused by the hyper-activation of innate immunity due to genetic factors occasionally leads to inflammatory keratinization diseases of the skin. Such inflammatory keratinization diseases with genetic autoinflammatory pathomechanisms are called “autoinflammatory keratinization diseases” (AiKDs). (Akiyama 2020)

SPRR2 proteins have been shown to protect against reactive oxygen species (ROS) in keratinocytes. It is shown that Sprr2f acts to dampen damage due to ROS in renal injury, likely from postinjury inflammation. A Sprr2f-KO mice show greater degree of fibrosis formation after UUO (unilateral ureteral obstruction). This could indicate an antif-ibrosis function of this gene. (Huynh et al. 2020)

ENSG00000134765 -> DSC1 desmocollin 1
l2fc: -8.05428 - padj: 1.37393e-17

The protein encoded by this gene is a calcium-dependent glycoprotein that is a member of the desmocollin subfamily of the cadherin superfamily. These desmosomal family members, along with the desmogleins, are found primarily in epithelial cells where they constitute the adhesive proteins of the desmosome cell-cell junction and are required for cell adhesion and desmosome formation.

It is shown that DSG1 inhibits skin inflammation by inhibiting the NF-κB signaling pathway. Various observations support that DSG1 deficiency is linked to inflammation. First, DSG1 deficiency has been reported in patients with atopic dermatitis and Netherton syndrome, which share chronic inflammatory dermatitis and allergic manifestations with SAMEC. Second, 2 siblings presented with Netherton syndrome and normal DSG1 epidermal staining, whereas no skin inflammation was observed. Third, DSG1 deficiency is probably responsible for the mucosal barrier impairment and inflammation observed in patients with eosinophilic esophagitis. (Polivka et al. 2018)

ENSG00000196407 -> THEM5 thioesterase superfamily member 5
l2fc: -3.84397 - padj 2.28808e-17

Enables palmitoyl-CoA hydrolase activity. Involved in long-chain fatty-acyl-CoA metabolic process. The enzyme is up-regulated during times of increased fatty acid oxidation.

In this paper it is reported that fatty acid oxidation lowers inflammation in macrophages. We suggest that this gene is therefore downregulated during inflammation caused by IL-17A. (Namgaladze and Brüne 2016)

ENSG00000010030 -> ETS variant transcription factor 7
l2fc: -2.62952 - padj: 3.22636e-17

The protein encoded by this gene belongs to the ETS family of transcription factors, which is a large group of evolutionarily conserved transcriptional regulators that play an important role in a variety of cellular processes throughout development and differentiation, and are involved in oncogenesis as well.

It is hypothesized that regulators, like ETV7, are important to prevent excessive inflammatory signaling. Again this gene is downregulated in treated cells. (Froggatt et al. 2021)

ENSG00000140519 -> RHCG Rh family C glycoprotein
l2fc: 3.55967 - padj: 3.41542e-17

Enables ammonium transmembrane transporter activity; ankyrin binding activity; and identical protein binding activity. Involved in ammonium transmembrane transport; cellular ion homeostasis; and transepithelial ammonium transport.

GO enrichment analysis (ORA)

We perform GO enrichment analysis (Biological Processes) with an ORA approach, utilizing a subset of genes that have a padj < 0.001 and a l2fc > 3.

From the resulting barplot we notice something interesting: the BP “epidermis development” seems to be highly upregulated, but the process “positive regulation of epidermis development” is indicated to be downregulated. This may indicate that, overall, treatment with IL_17A is anti-fibrogenic. This points in the direction of the results shown in the paper.

dds <- DESeq(dds)

## estimating dispersions
## found already estimated dispersions, replacing these
## gene-wise dispersion estimates

## final dispersion estimates

res<-res[!is.na(res$padj),]
SigExpGenes<-res[(res$padj < 0.001) & (abs(res$log2FoldChange)>3),]

KEGG enrichment analysis (ORA)

In this part we perform a pathway enrichment analysis using KEGG database. The following code will not be executed, it is included only as a reference to dispaly the methodology used. We performed the analysis based on three comparisons: IL17-A against control, TGF-β against control, and finally, IL17ATGFB against TGF-β. We chose these comparisons to be able to validate some of the results indicated in the paper.

dds <- DESeq(dds)
res <- results(dds,contrast = c('source_name_ch1','IL_17A','CTRL'))
res<-res[!is.na(res$padj),]
SigExpGenes<-res[(res$padj < 0.001) & (abs(res$log2FoldChange)>1),] 
rownames(SigExpGenes)%>%length #significally expressed genes
rownames(counts(dds))%>%length #all tested genes including NAs

search_kegg_organism('sapiens', by='scientific_name')

SigExpGenes$ENTREZID<-AnnotationDbi::mapIds(x=database,
                       keys = rownames(SigExpGenes),
                       column = "ENTREZID",
                       keytype = "ENSEMBL",
                       multiVals = "first")

kk <- enrichKEGG(gene         = SigExpGenes$ENTREZID,
                 organism     = 'hsa',
                 pAdjustMethod = "BH",
                 qvalueCutoff = 0.2,
                 pvalueCutoff = 0.05)

kkres<-as.data.frame(kk@result)

significantkkres<-kkres[kkres$pvalue<kk@pvalueCutoff & kkres$p.adjust<kk@pvalueCutoff & kkres$qvalue < kk@qvalueCutoff,2,drop=F]

geneList<-SigExpGenes$log2FoldChange
names(geneList)<-SigExpGenes$ENTREZID

download.pathway<-function(keggid){
folder<-"pics"
if (!("pics" %in% list.files())) {dir.create(folder)}
setwd(folder)
pic <- pathview(gene.data  = geneList,
                     pathway.id = keggid,
                     species    = stringr::str_extract(keggid,"[A-z]+"),
                     limit      = list(gene=max(abs(geneList)), cpd=1))
setwd("..")
}
rownames(significantkkres)
lapply(rownames(significantkkres),download.pathway)

For this last part we used a padj treshold of 0.05 to highlight better the effect that IL17-A had on the combined treatment.

First, let’s examine the Cytokine-cytokine receptor interaction, that was shown to be enriched in all three cases.

In the first image we can see significant enrichment of genes, like IL1F6, that are correlated to inflammation, and downregulation of others, like IL1F7, that are suppressors of inflammation. Another interesting gene that appears to be downregulated is GDF7. This gene encodes a secreted ligand of the TGF-beta. We therefore hypothesise that the downregulation of this gene may impair the effect of TGF-beta. This downregulation is still present in cells with both treatments. This could be correlated to a anti fibrogenic function of IL17-A. If we compare the first and second images we can see similar enriched genes, suggesting that IL17-A mantains his inflammatory functions even when paired with TGF in the treatment.

IL17-A - CRTL:

TGF-β - CRTL:

IL17ATGFB - TGF-β:

In the original paper it is indicated that an anti-fibrogenic function of IL17-A may be due to the downregulation of the wnt signaling. This effect is relevant even when comparing IL17ATGFB treated cells with TGF-β only.

IL17ATGFB - TGF-β:

We are also interested in assessing how the expression in the ECM-receptor interaction pathway is impacted by the treatments. As shown below, we can see that IL17-A does not impact the expression of collagen in any meaningful way. TGF does, with a strong upregulation. When comparing IL17ATGFB to TGF-β only, we can see that collagen levels are not impacted, but the level of laminin genes is overexpressed. Laminins support and influence the migration and the function of immune cells, enabling Leukocyte recruitment to sites of injury or inflammation. These observations support the idea expressed in the paper, that IL17 does not directly impact fibrogenesis by reducing collagen expression (even though a slight downregulation is present), but indirectly by impacting other pathways, like the wnt signaling pathway indicated before.
